    <title>Combined summary - BIP Proposal: Compact Client Side Filtering for Light Clients</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T01:35:56.641693+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-June/014549.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Developers in the bitcoin-dev forum have been discussing various proposals related to Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) drafts that focus on improving efficiency and user privacy. One such proposal is a new light client BIP by Lightning Labs, which aims to enable a lightweight back end for lightning on mobile devices while balancing usability with privacy concerns. The proposal includes a fixed false-positive rate and requests feedback on parameter selection for optimizing bandwidth utilization in relation to items scanned, block size, number of blocks fetched, and filter size.While some have raised concerns about privacy issues with bloom filters and light client modes, others have proposed new BIPs prioritizing user privacy, including Olaoluwa Osuntokun and Alex Akselrod's proposal which lacks a filter for unconfirmed transactions that BIP37 provides. The proposal also includes test vectors for different false-positive rates, and Alex Akselrod has created a JS calculator to explore the effect of tweaking the false positive rate.In addition, there have been discussions on the maintenance of an additional index of the chain by full-nodes, which serves as a compact filter to light clients. While there are debates about the benefits of weakly verifiable outpoints and pubkey hashes and whether they introduce attack vectors, developers are trying to balance usability with privacy concerns.There have also been debates around the use of SPV wallets, which rely on miners committing to a transaction to give users assurance that the transaction is valid, and the potential loss of privacy associated with this approach. Some have suggested that parsing all transactions and running in the background could address the issue without sacrificing privacy.Overall, the discussions highlight ongoing efforts to improve the functionality, security, and user experience of Bitcoin. Lightning Labs has made changes to the Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) and proposes a new light client mode to improve efficiency and user privacy. During email exchanges, concerns were raised about weakly verifiable outpoints and pubkey hashes posing an attack vector. The possibility of full nodes lying by omission was highlighted in a BIP leading to denial of service and undesirable failure modes in applications that rely on certain on-chain events. An additional index of the chain by full-nodes is also discussed.The Bitcoin Wallet app shows at least 2 million wallets depending on BIP37 with instant notification being the most requested feature. Privacy issues are raised in BIP37, suggesting developers should prioritize user privacy. A discussion about product usability highlights the difference between personal and user behavior.On the mailing list, privacy leaks in the bitcoin protocol were raised, with Tom Zander calling the claim that bloom filters are a "total loss of privacy" baseless. Jonas Nick gave a presentation on privacy leaks in bitcoin protocol, covering SPV and bloom query problem specifics, and referenced a research paper titled "On the Privacy Provisions of Bloom Filters in Lightweight Bitcoin Clients" which shows that existing SPV clients leak considerable information about the addresses of Bitcoin users by relying on Bloom filters.</summary>
